# Constructors overloading
    When you're working with a real-world system, the same object may need to be created in different ways depending on the situation.
    Let’s say you’re building a system for managing employee records. Sometimes, you only have the employee’s name. Other times,
    you might have their name and ID. In some cases, you’ll have the full information including department and salary.

    Creating different classes for each case would be inefficient and repetitive. What you really need is a way to use the same class
    and initialize it differently based on what information is available. This is where constructor overloading becomes useful.
    It gives you the flexibility to create objects in multiple ways without duplicating code or breaking your class design.

Q1. What Exactly Is Constructor Overloading? 💡
Standard Definition:
    Constructor overloading in Java means having more than one constructor in the same class — but each constructor has a different set of parameters.

# Key Takeaways 📝:

    1. Constructor overloading allows you to create multiple constructors in one class
    2. Each constructor has a different parameter list
    3. Java picks the right constructor based on the arguments you pass when creating the object
    4. It makes your code easier to use, more flexible, and cleaner
    5. You can offer both simple and detailed ways to create objects without repeating code

# Common Interview Questions & Answers 💬

    Q1: What is constructor overloading in Java?
        Constructor overloading means writing multiple constructors in the same class, each with a different set of parameters.

    Q2: Can two constructors have the same parameters?
        No. Each constructor must be unique in terms of the number or type of parameters.

    Q3: How does Java know which constructor to use?
        Java chooses the constructor based on the number and type of arguments passed during object creation.

    Q4: Is constructor overloading required?
        No, but it makes your class more flexible and helps avoid writing multiple classes or complex logic.

    Q5: Can I overload constructors and still have a default one?
        Yes. You can keep the default constructor along with other overloaded constructors. This is very common.



# Program flow with various components

Q1. What Is Java Program Flow?
Standard Definition:
    Java Program Flow refers to the exact sequence in which Java executes different parts of your code — from class loading to object creation to method execution.

Simple Explanation:
    Think of your Java program like a stage play:
        1. The crew (static blocks) sets up the scene before the actors come in.
        2. The play starts (main() method runs).
        3. New actors (objects) enter — they put on makeup (instance variables), change costumes (instance blocks), and then say their first line (constructor).
        4. Then, the story progresses through scenes (methods).

# Key Takeaways:

    1. Static blocks run once when the class is loaded.
    2. main() is the first method that runs in your program.
    3. Creating an object triggers:
        i. Instance variable initialization
       ii. Instance block
      iii. Constructor
    4. Instance methods can only be used after the object is created.
    5. Java always follows the same order — so once you learn it, you won’t forget it.

# Common Interview Questions:

    Q1: What runs first — static block or main()?
        Static block. It runs when the class is loaded — before main().

    Q2: What happens when you create an object?
        First, instance variables are initialized, then the instance block runs, and finally the constructor runs.

    Q3: What’s the difference between static and instance methods?
        Static methods belong to the class and can run without creating an object. Instance methods need an object.

    Q4: Can a class have multiple static blocks?
        Yes. They will run in the order they appear — but still only once when the class is loaded.

    Q5: Do instance blocks run before or after the constructor?
        Before. Instance blocks run immediately after instance variables are initialized, and just before the constructor.

# Conclusion:

    In this program, you saw how Java follows a strict and predictable order when executing code inside a class.
    It starts by handling all static parts of the class — static variables and static blocks — before anything else.
    This happens only once, when the class is loaded.

    Once the static parts are done, Java enters the main() method, which is where your actual program starts running.

    When you create an object using the new keyword, Java performs three important steps in order:
        1. It initializes the instance variables.
        2. Then it runs the instance block.
        3. Finally, it calls the constructor.

    This example is a great way to understand that object creation in Java isn’t just one step — it’s a process.
    And knowing the exact order helps you write better, cleaner, and more predictable code.

    The more you understand how Java works behind the scenes, the more confident you’ll be as a developer.

    Keep this order in mind: static block → main() → instance block → constructor
